ğŸ¯ Think of it like this:

Keyword	Can change array contents?	Can reassign to new array?	Example

var	âœ… Yes	âœ… Yes	var arr = [1]; arr.push(2); arr = [3];
let	âœ… Yes	âœ… Yes	let arr = [1]; arr.push(2); arr = [3];
const	âœ… Yes	âŒ No	const arr = [1]; arr.push(2); arr = [3]; // Error



---

ğŸ’¬ In short:

Use let when you expect to reassign the variable (like swapping arrays, counters, etc.)

Use const for arrays and objects that shouldnâ€™t be reassigned, only modified inside.

Avoid var in modern JavaScript (itâ€™s old and confusing with scoping).



